   <div class="jumbotron">
      <h1>
         HAMER 2026 <br />
         <small>May 8-9 2026</small><br />
         <small>MIT Room 66-110 / Consulate General of Greece in Boston</small>
      </h1>
      

         <p>Following the success of the inaugural Hellenic-American Meeting of 
         Early-Career Researchers (HAMER) Symposium, the Circle of 
         Hellenic Academics in Boston is pleased to announce the second HAMER Symposium!<br /><br />
 
         HAMER 2026 will take place on <b>May 8–9 at MIT Room 66-110</b>. The 
         goal of the Symposium is to provide a forum for early-career 
         professionals of Greek descent to present their academic work and 
         business ideas, receive feedback, and network as they consider their 
         next career steps.<br /><br />

         The first HAMER Symposium attracted a distinguished group of participants from 
         leading universities and institutions and provided an important forum 
         for dialogue, collaboration, and the presentation of emerging research 
         by members of the Hellenic academic and professional community. 
         Building on this strong foundation, the upcoming symposium aims to 
         further strengthen these connections and expand opportunities for 
         academic exchange and professional development.<br /><br />

         The HAMER Symposium was conceived and is organized by the <a href="https://www.hellenic-academics.org/">Circle of 
         Hellenic Academics in Boston</a>, with the 
         support of a student committee. It is also co-sponsored by HBA-USA 
         (Hellenic Bioscientific Association of the USA) and HIAS 
         (Hellenic Institute for Advanced Study).<br /><br />


         <strong>Scope:</strong> The event will feature research presentations by students and early career researchers, loosely defined as within 
         5 years from the completion of their PhD degree. Participation from the broader academic/research community, 
         independently of their career stage, is expected. This will be an opportunity to connect and to foster collaborative 
         research within the broader Hellenic-American academic community. Research presentations in any area of 
         science, engineering and the humanities are welcome! <br /><br />
         
         <strong>Awards:</strong> The organizing committee will also award two prizes for the two best research presentations at 
         the event. Each prize will cover round-trip airfare for the award recipient to visit an academic or 
         research institution in Greece! These awards are sponsored by Leta Serafim in honor of the 
         memory of her husband Philip Serafim, professor at Northeastern University and National Technical University of Athens.<br /><br />

         <strong>Travel Grants:</strong> A limited number of travel grants will 
         be offered to out-of-town participants. Applicants can apply for a travel
         grant by filling out the appropriate section of the <a href='#submission'>abstract submission
         form<a/>.

      </p>
